[1
Date: Thu 2 Mar 2000
From: Tomas Jelinek, MD DTMP <jelinek@lrz.uni-muenchen.de>

In view of the recent change in CDC guidelines regarding malaria
chemoprophylaxis for the Dominican Republic, we wish to report another
patient with falciparum malaria who was reproted today within our network
TropNetEurop. The case was reported by Martin Grobusch (M.D., M.Sc.,
DTM&H), from Berlin.
This 45-year-old male patient spent a fortnight holiday in a brand new 5
star beach resort named near Punta Cana from 28 Jan 2000 to 10 Feb 2000.
He decided not to take any malaria prophylaxis although he had heard about
the recent case cluster. He fell ill on day 13 after return with fever,
chills and headache and presented to a peripheral hospital in Berlin a few
days later as
reported where malaria was suspected by himself and his attending
physician. Slides were first prepared and screened in the local laboratory,
and a preliminary diagnosis of _Plasmodium falciparum_ malaria was
established which was confirmed later when the slides were reviewed later
by an expert microscopist (M.G.) at our institution to which the patient
was referred. The patient reported that the resort has still been
partiallly under construction, and that it has been built on the grounds of
a former village which was swept away by hurricane George.
Including this recent case, a total of 13 patients with falciparum malaria
acquired at the East coast of Dominican Republic have been reported within
TropNetEurop since 27 Nov 1999. Out of these, 10 patients came from
Germany, 2 from Spain, and one from Austria. Within TropNetEurop, we
continue to monitor the situation.
--
Tomas Jelinek, MD DTMP
University of Munich
Department of Infectious Diseases and Tropical Medicine
Leopoldstr. 5, 80802 Munich, Germany
Tel: (x49)-89-2180 3830 / 3517, Fax: (x49)-89-33 61 12
<jelinek@lrz.uni-muenchen.de>
